<h2>1. Acknowledge your feelings
</h2>

<p>It helps to firsts sit with your feelings and acknowledge them. Take a deep breath in and out. It’s ok to not want to do something or find something hard. All of us struggle with doing things, and that’s ok. 
</p>

<p>If you don’t want to do something, you probably have a valid reason. Our feelings are like indicators, they tell us whether something is safe, exciting or dangerous, and help to keep us safe, but they’re not rules. We don’t have to follow our emotions if we don’t want to, but they can help us make a decision.
</p>

<p>So, it is good to check in and acknowledge those feelings. Sometimes we can throw ourselves into things without checking in with how it’s making us feel, which can leave us doing things that aren’t right for us.
</p>

<p>Other times we might acknowledge our feelings, but we judge them, and often ourselves, creating an extra burden.
</p>

<p>So when you sit with your feelings, try to accept them as they are, warts and all.
</p>

<p>A good example of this is looking at trees. Trees come in all shapes; some are twisted, some are missing branches, some have been knocked over by the wind. They are all trees. Not good, not bad. Just trees. Your feelings are the same. Not good, not bad. Just feelings.
</p>

