<h2>2. Why do you not want to do the thing?
</h2>

<p>Once you’ve sat with your emotions, you might realise that there’s a reason you don’t want to do something, but you’re not entirely sure what that is.
</p>

<p>Sometimes the biggest the obstacle is finding out what is stopping us.
</p>

<p>It could be that we feel tired and lack the physical or emotional energy to do our task. 
</p>

<p>It might be that we’re afraid of getting it wrong, and what people could think of us. 
</p>

<p>We might have a “block” and not know how to get started, or what we should be doing. 
</p>

<p>Or it could be that someone has told us to do it, and it doesn’t align with our values.
</p>

<p>These are all valid responses. Whatever your reason is there is probably something you can do about it (including the option of not doing the thing). If you need some help in finding out what do, writing things down can help us process and order our thoughts, and help us find solutions.
</p>

<p>And if you’re <a href="/blogs/Having-a-bad-day__-Try-these-5-tips">feeling down, try these 5 tips.</a></p>

